stix:STIX_Header.stix:Title: H-Worm RAT Associated Command and Control Servers
stix:STIX_Header.stix:Description:
The following information provides command and control servers/hosts used by the H-Worm remote administration tool (RAT) variant as of 09 June 2014. H-Worm RAT is a Visual Basic script (VBS) file, often wrapped, in a PE dropper. The payload is obfuscated with custom and standard Base64 encoding. The network callback includes sensitive system information including, but not limited to: disk volume serial, host name, Operating System, AV product, and current system date information concatenated in a delimited (<|>) sequence in the User-Agent string.
Some of the campaigns described in the referenced blog entry are reported in addition to unique campaigns independently observed by a trusted third party. The majority of the infections were from the "plus" campaign, which includes "<|>plus<|>" in the User-Agent string in a HTTP POST request back to the command and control (C2) system. There was also a campaign that contained "<|>underworld final<|>" in place of plus. Other campaigns had "I_AM_READY" and "ready" as the keyword on the HTTP POST request.
In addition, the "ready" campaign delimited the User-Agent information with "\" instead of "<|>". As reported in the blog post, the User-Agent of the initial HTTP POST request contained the following information:
{DiskVolumeSerial}<|>{Hostname}<|>{Username}<|>{OS}<|>plus<|>{AVProductInstalled or nan-av}<|>{USBSpread: true or false} - {CurrentSystemDate}
Please see FireEye posting on the H-Worm RAT for additional background information.
http://www.fireeye.com/blog/technical/threat-intelligence/2013/09/now-you-see-me-h-worm-by-houdini.html
